WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:12.920
Hello, I'm Jiyoung Seo, a doctoral student in Learning Design Technology program at Penn

00:00:12.920 --> 00:00:18.600
State, and I was one of the interns at RStudio in 2020.

00:00:18.600 --> 00:00:23.719
I've been using R without sight, because I'm blind.

00:00:23.719 --> 00:00:29.320
Yeah, I understand that you might have a big question mark in mind.

00:00:29.320 --> 00:00:35.320
How a blind person could do data science, or even use computer?

00:00:35.320 --> 00:00:41.279
In this talk, I will answer the fundamental questions that you might have by demonstrating

00:00:41.279 --> 00:00:48.480
some strategies that I've used, plus by introducing some accessibility improvements made for RStudio

00:00:48.480 --> 00:00:53.080
IDE and Shiny that I was involved in for my internship.

00:00:53.080 --> 00:00:58.520
Okay, let's get started.

00:00:58.520 --> 00:01:06.120
Before talking about R and data science, let me address this question first.

00:01:06.120 --> 00:01:07.919
How do I use computer?

00:01:07.919 --> 00:01:14.080
Well, I need to ask you back, then how do you use your computer?

00:01:14.080 --> 00:01:21.040
In other words, how do you interact with computer?

00:01:21.040 --> 00:01:27.480
We could break down the way we interact with computer into input and output.

00:01:27.480 --> 00:01:36.199
That is, how we pass information to computer, and how we get information from computer.

00:01:36.199 --> 00:01:43.400
What if we would remove visual aspect from the two modes of interactions?

00:01:43.400 --> 00:01:51.239
Undoubtedly, using mouse would become almost impossible, or even useless.

00:01:51.239 --> 00:01:58.239
I doubt no one could point and double click RStudio icon on their desktop in a stable

00:01:58.239 --> 00:02:05.879
fashion when blindfolded, but you can still use keyboard as long as your muscle memory

00:02:05.879 --> 00:02:09.720
remembers your keyboard layout.

00:02:09.720 --> 00:02:12.279
What about output?

00:02:12.279 --> 00:02:19.639
We need some workarounds alternative to visual monitor.

00:02:19.639 --> 00:02:24.520
How about using sound output instead?

00:02:24.520 --> 00:02:37.360
I use computer via keyboard-only input and sound and tactile output, just like this.

00:02:37.360 --> 00:02:39.279
Isn't it too fast for you?

00:02:39.279 --> 00:02:43.279
No worries, let me slow it down for you.

00:02:49.639 --> 00:03:16.600
Now that you got how I interact with computer, let's talk about data science.

00:03:16.600 --> 00:03:23.279
Data science involves a cycle of interaction with data, such as importing, tidying, transforming,

00:03:23.279 --> 00:03:26.479
visualizing, and modeling.

00:03:26.479 --> 00:03:29.479
And it feels like data science is highly vision-dominant.

00:03:29.479 --> 00:03:33.479
Yes, it could be.

00:03:33.479 --> 00:03:39.520
But data science is more than what is seen.

00:03:39.520 --> 00:03:47.360
If data science was restricted to only vision domain, that would mean that people who cannot

00:03:47.360 --> 00:03:53.360
employ vision sense can't do data science at all.

00:03:53.360 --> 00:04:01.440
Very fortunately, however, that is not true, because we have R, which enables blind people

00:04:01.440 --> 00:04:06.720
see data beyond visual models.

00:04:06.720 --> 00:04:13.759
I believe R is one of the most accessible data science environments because of the following

00:04:13.759 --> 00:04:15.160
benefits.

00:04:15.160 --> 00:04:19.079
First, command line interface.

00:04:19.079 --> 00:04:27.399
As opposed to point-and-click graphical user interface, which requires mouse input interaction,

00:04:27.399 --> 00:04:31.459
R is a command line environment.

00:04:31.459 --> 00:04:37.660
This means that you can do everything within terminal using keyboard only.

00:04:37.660 --> 00:04:41.700
This is a good benefit for keyboard users like me.

00:04:41.700 --> 00:04:49.579
Second, the beautiful interplay between reproducibility and accessibility.

00:04:49.579 --> 00:04:57.660
R Markdown is a plain text-based document for reproducible report that can be written

00:04:57.700 --> 00:05:06.859
with any text editor and can be rendered into multiple formats, including HTML, Word, PDF,

00:05:06.859 --> 00:05:09.980
EPUB, and more.

00:05:09.980 --> 00:05:17.380
These outputs, in many cases, are made readily accessible to assistive technologies.

00:05:17.380 --> 00:05:23.380
Especially, the HTML output is super accessible.

00:05:23.579 --> 00:05:30.859
Last but not least, there are a number of accessible packages out there, thanks to its

00:05:30.859 --> 00:05:36.700
open-source nature.

00:05:36.700 --> 00:05:43.339
There are two either accessible or semi-accessible integrated development environments supporting

00:05:43.339 --> 00:05:45.299
R programming.

00:05:45.299 --> 00:05:50.399
One is RStudio IDE, version 1.3 or later.

00:05:50.399 --> 00:05:57.480
The other one is Visual Studio Code with some extensions for R.

00:05:57.480 --> 00:06:02.799
It was such an honor for me to be part of the RStudio accessibility project for my summer

00:06:02.799 --> 00:06:13.440
2020 internship, under the great double mentorship of Gary Ritchie on RStudio team and Winston

00:06:13.440 --> 00:06:17.059
Chang on Shiny team.

00:06:17.059 --> 00:06:23.140
Since RStudio has just started its accessibility support, there are still rooms for further

00:06:23.140 --> 00:06:30.339
improvements, but we can at least recommend trying out RStudio Server for keyboard or

00:06:30.339 --> 00:06:39.260
screen reader users to benefit from its accessibility enhancements.

00:06:39.260 --> 00:06:46.899
As RStudio Server requires Linux system, Windows users need virtual technology called Windows

00:06:46.899 --> 00:06:53.700
subsystem for Linux, and we published the technical details for this.

00:06:53.700 --> 00:06:58.260
Just check it out.

00:06:58.260 --> 00:07:04.220
Here are some accessibility options currently supported in RStudio Server version 1.3 or

00:07:04.220 --> 00:07:06.220
higher.

00:07:06.220 --> 00:07:15.700
We have added screen reader support, animation reduction, tab key focus control, etc.

00:07:15.700 --> 00:07:21.380
And previously, it was very challenging for keyboard users to move their focus around,

00:07:21.380 --> 00:07:27.339
but now you can get your focus moved around by pressing tab key from menu bar all the

00:07:27.339 --> 00:07:31.579
way down to workbench area.

00:07:31.579 --> 00:07:41.059
You can send any inquiries or suggestions directly to accessibility at rstudio.com.

00:07:41.059 --> 00:07:47.220
Now it's time to introduce some accessible and useful R packages that I've used.

00:07:47.220 --> 00:07:56.820
I used GT when interacting with DataFrame and other tidy data table, and I used Sonify

00:07:56.820 --> 00:08:02.859
for two-dimensional scatterplot or line charts.

00:08:02.859 --> 00:08:12.260
Braille R package is very useful for understanding histogram, bar plot, and box plot.

00:08:12.260 --> 00:08:18.579
Shiny, it used to be not very accessible, but it's getting accessible.

00:08:18.579 --> 00:08:24.779
So of course, I use it for interactive data science work.

00:08:24.779 --> 00:08:31.579
R Markdown is such an accessible Swiss army knife because you can do almost everything

00:08:31.579 --> 00:08:36.979
possible in R and turn it into accessible outputs.

00:08:36.979 --> 00:08:47.659
All right, let me walk you through each of them from how I interact with DataFrame.

00:08:47.659 --> 00:08:55.299
I assume view is one of the most widely used basic functions among R users to get a better

00:08:55.299 --> 00:08:58.979
sense of DataFrame structure.

00:08:58.979 --> 00:09:08.179
Unfortunately, the default data viewer called from urls package is completely inaccessible.

00:09:08.179 --> 00:09:14.900
This means that screen reader does not read anything for you from the default pane.

00:09:14.900 --> 00:09:24.260
RStudio has replaced this default one with their one enhanced data viewer, which is accessible.

00:09:24.260 --> 00:09:34.859
However, that's not universal solution for those who do not use RStudio IDE.

00:09:34.859 --> 00:09:41.700
My simple go-to is GT, developed by Rich and Joe.

00:09:41.700 --> 00:09:51.020
GT stands for grammar of tables, and it has a lot of number of good features that helps

00:09:51.020 --> 00:09:56.099
you create nice looking tables.

00:09:56.099 --> 00:10:02.539
But I use its core function, GT colon colon GT in lieu of data viewer.

00:10:02.539 --> 00:10:04.580
Why I use this?

00:10:04.580 --> 00:10:11.179
Because it generates and opens on HTML table, which is fully screen reader accessible and

00:10:11.179 --> 00:10:14.979
keyboard users.

00:10:15.979 --> 00:10:28.500
Next, I'll talk about how I interpret two dimensional scatter plot.

00:10:28.500 --> 00:10:36.340
On the left hand side, we have a simple scatter plot with x and y axes.

00:10:36.340 --> 00:10:44.260
How would you be able to represent this visualization in a way that blind people could also digest?

00:10:44.539 --> 00:10:46.580
How about using sound?

00:10:46.580 --> 00:10:54.460
Say for example, we could represent values on x-axis using stereo panning sound from

00:10:54.460 --> 00:10:56.539
left to right.

00:10:56.539 --> 00:11:03.179
And we could map y-axis values with different pitch.

00:11:03.179 --> 00:11:08.219
Data points that are higher on the graph have a higher pitch.

00:11:08.219 --> 00:11:15.140
Data points that are lower on the graph have corresponding lower pitch.

00:11:15.140 --> 00:11:23.500
Just take a listen.

00:11:23.500 --> 00:11:27.299
It makes sense, doesn't it?

00:11:27.299 --> 00:11:33.099
This technique that represents data using sound is called sonification.

00:11:33.099 --> 00:11:39.539
I use data sonification alternative to data visualization.

00:11:39.539 --> 00:11:52.219
We can also try this out with sonify package developed by Stephan Siegert and Robin Williams.

00:11:52.219 --> 00:12:01.619
Next, I will show you how I interact with histogram.

00:12:01.619 --> 00:12:04.859
Here is a visual histogram.

00:12:04.859 --> 00:12:08.299
How could we make it accessible to people who are blind?

00:12:08.299 --> 00:12:17.179
Yes, of course, we can use data sonification again by mapping x and y-axis to sounds.

00:12:17.179 --> 00:12:24.380
But I would like to introduce another way of data representation this time.

00:12:24.380 --> 00:12:29.359
That is using text description.

00:12:29.359 --> 00:12:36.119
The braille R package developed by Jonathan Guthrie has a function that translates some

00:12:36.119 --> 00:12:42.280
R graphs into alternative text description.

00:12:42.280 --> 00:12:50.359
You can call this function by vi, which stands for vision impairment.

00:12:50.359 --> 00:12:57.200
This package is currently available on GitHub that you can install via remote colon colon

00:12:57.200 --> 00:13:02.760
install on the bar GitHub function.

00:13:02.760 --> 00:13:13.440
For box plot interaction, we can apply the same method to this visualization.

00:13:13.440 --> 00:13:15.520
Just like this.

00:13:15.520 --> 00:13:22.840
I know we got a quite long description this time, but it's cool that we can have auto-generated

00:13:22.840 --> 00:13:27.039
alt text for some basic R graphs.

00:13:27.039 --> 00:13:34.000
If you are an R developer, please help Jonathan Guthrie on GitHub to support more types of

00:13:34.000 --> 00:13:35.000
graphs.

00:13:35.000 --> 00:13:44.679
Okay, I want to turn into accessible math content interaction.

00:13:44.679 --> 00:13:52.159
I kept mentioning that R Markdown contributes to accessibility.

00:13:52.159 --> 00:13:58.880
One of the most pleasant supports is accessible math.

00:13:58.880 --> 00:14:10.200
For HTML output, R Markdown uses MathJax JS library by default for latex math expressions.

00:14:10.200 --> 00:14:18.280
And this is rendered into accessible math markup language content that is fully accessible

00:14:18.280 --> 00:14:26.559
with modern screen readers.

00:14:26.559 --> 00:14:31.440
I'm going to talk a little bit about Shiny.

00:14:31.440 --> 00:14:36.940
I'm super excited to announce that Shiny is getting accessible.

00:14:36.940 --> 00:14:43.000
With the amazing support of Winston, Carson, Barrett, and other Shiny team members, I was

00:14:43.000 --> 00:14:48.919
working for making Shiny accessible for my internship activity at RStudio.

00:14:48.919 --> 00:14:55.400
As a result, you will see many accessibility improvements in the next Shiny release, version

00:14:55.400 --> 00:14:59.039
1.6 or higher.

00:14:59.039 --> 00:15:05.119
If you want to test the development version, that's available on GitHub, and you can install

00:15:05.119 --> 00:15:10.440
it through remote package.

00:15:10.440 --> 00:15:14.320
Some significant improvements are as follows.

00:15:14.320 --> 00:15:22.039
First, we've added PayPal's bootstrap accessibility plugin under the hood.

00:15:22.039 --> 00:15:32.679
So alert, tooltip, popover, model dialogue, dropdown, tab panel, collapse, and carousel

00:15:32.679 --> 00:15:37.320
elements are made keyboard accessible.

00:15:38.200 --> 00:15:46.039
Next, there are many significant improvements made for Shiny widgets.

00:15:46.039 --> 00:15:55.960
Select input, especially selectize input, file input are now fully keyboard accessible.

00:15:55.960 --> 00:16:03.559
Font awesome and glyphic icon now produces appropriate labels based on icon names for

00:16:03.559 --> 00:16:06.919
screen readers.

00:16:06.919 --> 00:16:17.880
Media buttons and checkbox group input are properly grouped together for assistive technologies.

00:16:17.880 --> 00:16:25.200
Date input and date range input are properly labeled.

00:16:25.200 --> 00:16:33.559
And now dynamic contents within all the output and update input are auto announced to screen

00:16:33.559 --> 00:16:41.640
readers and refreshable bread display.

00:16:41.640 --> 00:16:47.919
There are also some great enhancements for semantic accessibility.

00:16:47.919 --> 00:16:55.719
We can pass alt text to render plot function to specify alternative text description for

00:16:55.719 --> 00:16:58.960
screen readers.

00:16:58.960 --> 00:17:02.760
It could be a static text.

00:17:02.760 --> 00:17:06.520
Not object is given by default.

00:17:06.520 --> 00:17:14.199
Or you can even use reactive function for alt term to create dynamic text that is useful

00:17:14.199 --> 00:17:22.640
when you want to create reactive alt text in response to user input.

00:17:22.680 --> 00:17:32.920
And you can explicitly set the lang code, language code, used within your Shiny app

00:17:32.920 --> 00:17:38.319
by passing lang parameter to float page function.

00:17:38.319 --> 00:17:47.400
This helps search engine parsers and assistive tech better identify document language.

00:17:47.400 --> 00:17:54.520
Last but not least, semantic landmarks have been applied to main panel as well as sidebar

00:17:54.520 --> 00:18:07.719
panel for screen readers to quickly navigate through Shiny apps in a logical manner.

00:18:07.719 --> 00:18:10.959
It's time to close my talk.

00:18:10.959 --> 00:18:18.400
I have touched upon some fundamental questions that you might have.

00:18:18.400 --> 00:18:21.400
How could a blind person do computer?

00:18:21.400 --> 00:18:26.479
And how could a blind person do data science?

00:18:26.479 --> 00:18:32.680
As my presentation title suggests, we can make data science accessible beyond visual

00:18:32.680 --> 00:18:41.760
models because data science requires insight, not sight.

00:18:41.760 --> 00:18:46.520
And all is possible with R.

00:18:46.520 --> 00:18:54.199
According to the World Health Organization's 2018 report, globally, more than 1.3 billion

00:18:54.199 --> 00:19:01.880
people have some varying degree of visual impairment and 36 million of whom are blind.

00:19:01.880 --> 00:19:04.719
I'm just one of them.

00:19:04.719 --> 00:19:14.920
Why not we invite more people with diverse abilities to use R and to enjoy data sciencing?

00:19:14.920 --> 00:19:15.479
Thank you.

